<Layout title="About - Myconoid Minis">
  <main class="container mx-auto px-4 py-8">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
      
      <!-- Hero Section -->
      <div class="text-center mb-12">
        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-6">About the Dragon Guy</h1>
        <div class="mb-8">
          <!-- Responsive image -->
          <img 
            src="/images/minis/IMG_4260.png" 
            alt="Nerd at work" 
            class="w-80 h-80 sm:w-64 sm:h-64 md:w-150 md:h-150 mx-auto object-cover shadow-lg rounded-lg"/>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Main Content -->

      <!-- Main Content with custom divider -->
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-12 relative">
          
        <!-- Vertical line (hidden on mobile, visible on large screens) -->
        <div class="hidden lg:block absolute left-1/2 top-0 bottom-0 w-px bg-gradient-to-b from-transparent via-gray-300 to-transparent dark:via-gray-600 transform -translate-x-1/2"></div>
        
        <!-- Bio Section -->
        <div class="lg:pr-12">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-6">My Journey</h2>
          <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
            <p>
              Welcome, traveler! I'm myconoid (aka Lars), and I like making miniature monsters for my tabletop games. What started as a hobby has grown into a pursuit of bringing tiny baddies to life for others!
            </p>
            <p>
              I specialize in creating grim-looking baddies for old school role-playing (OSR) and other games. 
            </p>
            <p>
              When I'm not making your favorite antagonists, you can find me riding motorbikes, digging in the garden and playing with my dog.
            </p>

          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Techniques & Philosophy -->
        <div class="lg:pl-12">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-6">My Approach</h2>
          <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
            <p>
              I like to keep things simple around here. You instantly know OSR-style artwork by its bold black and white "color" scheme. My minis take this into 3 dimensions with matte black priming and simple dry brushing to bring details out. 
            </p>
            <p>
              You can keep it real and play with them as is (and as Crom intended), or slap on some speedpaint to make them fancy.
            </p>
             <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
              <li>• Print with ABS-Like Resin</li>
              <li>• Airbrush polyurethane or acrylic primer</li>
              <li>• Two-part dry brush with grey and white acrylic</li>
              <li>• Summon the spirts to inhabit them</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

